{"title_page": "St Albans Abbey railway station", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox UK station\n| name         = St Albans Abbey\n| symbol       = rail\n| image_name   = St Albans Abbey railway station in 2009.jpg\n| code         = SAA\n| dft_category = F1\n| manager      = [[West Midlands Trains|London Northwestern Railway]]\n| locale       = [[St Albans]]\n| borough      = [[City of St Albans|St Albans]]\n| coordinates  = {{coord|51.7447|-0.3426|type:railwaystation_region:GB_scale:10000|display=inline,title}}\n<!-- | usage0405    = 0.175\n| usage0506    = {{increase}} 0.187\n| usage0607    = {{increase}} 0.207\n| usage0708    = {{increase}} 0.222\n| usage0809    = {{decrease}} 0.218\n| usage0910    = {{decrease}} 0.177\n| usage1011    = {{increase}} 0.185\n| usage1112    = {{increase}} 0.199\n| usage1213    = {{decrease}} 0.195\n| usage1314    = {{decrease}} 0.180 -->\n| usage1415    = {{decrease}} 0.142\n| usage1516    = {{increase}} 0.165\n| usage1617    = {{steady}} 0.165\n| usage1718    = {{increase}} 0.169\n| usage1819    = {{decrease}} 0.167\n| platforms    = 1\n| original     = [[London and North Western Railway]]<ref name=\"Butt\">{{harvnb|Butt|1995|p=202}}</ref>\n| postgroup    = [[London Midland and Scottish Railway|LMS]]\n| years        = 5 May 1858\n| events       = Opened as '''St Albans'''<ref name=\"Butt\" />\n| years1       = 2 June 1924\n| events1      = Renamed as '''St Albans Abbey'''<ref name=\"Butt\" />\n| years2       =\n| events2      =\n| gridref      = TL145063\n}}\n'''St Albans Abbey railway station''' in [[St Albans]], [[Hertfordshire]], England is about {{convert|0.6|mi|km|0}} south of the city centre in the St Stephen's area. It is the terminus of the [[Abbey Line]] from [[Watford Junction station|Watford Junction]], operated by [[West Midlands Trains|London Northwestern Railway]]. It is one of two stations in [[St Albans]], the other being the much larger and busier [[St Albans City railway station|St Albans City]].\n\nThe unstaffed station consists of a single open-air platform and a car park. Improvement works were carried out in 2008.\n\nIt was the second UK railway station to receive a [[Harrington Hump]] to improve [[accessibility]].<ref>{{cite news|title=UK Rail Station Installs Harrington Hump|url=http://www.railway-technology.com/news/news61899.html|accessdate=5 December 2011|newspaper=Railway-Technology.com|date=14 August 2009}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Dunstable, Hertford, Hitchin & St Albans RJD 35.jpg|thumb|left|A 1902 [[Railway Clearing House]] map of railways in the vicinity of St Albans Abbey (lower left, shown here as ''L.&N.W.'')]]\n{{St Albans railway stations}}\n[[File:S Albans Abbey 6 77479 1.jpg|thumb|right|St Albans Abbey station in June 1977]]\n\n\nSt Albans Abbey was the first railway station in St Albans, built by the [[London and North Western Railway]] in 1858.  It was, as it is now, a terminus; the company's plans to extend northwards to [[Luton]] and [[Dunstable]] never materialised.  Although the [[Midland Railway]] opened their station (St Albans City) in 1868, it was not until 1924 that \"Abbey\" was added to the station's title to avoid confusion - by this stage, both stations were owned by the [[London, Midland and Scottish Railway]].\n\nUntil November 2007 responsibility for the branch line was with Silverlink.\n\nRestoration of the passing loop at Bricket Wood was being considered by the local authorities and Network Rail but was turned down in early 2008; this would have facilitated trains running every 30 minutes.\n\n=== Branch to Hatfield ===\nIn 1865, the [[Great Northern Railway (Great Britain)|Great Northern Railway]] supported a group of local landowners to open a [[Hatfield and St Albans Railway|branch line from Hatfield to St Albans Abbey]] with an intermediate stop at [[St Albans (London Road) railway station|St Albans London Road]], and later at {{rws|Smallford}} (1866), {{rws|Salvation Army Halt}} (1901), {{rws|Hill End}} (1899), {{rws|Nast Hyde Halt}} (1910) and {{rws|Lemsford Road Halt}} (1942).  This line closed to passengers in 1951.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.subbrit.org.uk/sb-sites/stations/s/st_albans_london_road/index.shtml |title=Subterranea Britannica: SB-Sites: St. Albans London Road |accessdate=28 February 2007 |date=23 March 2006 |author=Nick Catford}}</ref> Goods services were withdrawn from the end of 1968<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stacc.org.uk/albanway/AW%20Map%20v2.1.pdf |title=The Alban Way |access-date=28 February 2007 |format=PDF |publisher=St Albans Cycle Campaign |date=21 July 2005 |page=1 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070104220214/http://www.stacc.org.uk/albanway/AW%20Map%20v2.1.pdf |archive-date=4 January 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and the track was lifted.  In the mid-1980s, the route was opened as a cycle path, now the [[Alban Way]]. The remains of the branch can be seen to the left of the single platform when looking down the line in the direction of [[Watford Junction]], including overgrown remnants of the second platform which would have served the branch.\n\n==Station masters==\n{{Div col}}\n*Frederick Facer ca. 1864  - ca. 1866\n*Edward Orchard ca. 1869 - 1875\n*Andrew Dunleary 1875<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=King\u2019s Langley Testimonial |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0001073/18750306/062/0005 |newspaper=Hemel Hempstead Gazette and West Herts Advertiser |location=England |date=6 March 1875 |access-date=7 March 2020 |via=British Newspaper Archive |url-access=subscription  }}</ref> - ???? (formerly station master at King\u2019s Langley)\n*Mr. Welton ???? - 1890<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Berkhampstead |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0001091/18900902/175/0008 |newspaper=Leighton Buzzard Observer and Linslade Gazette |location=England |date=2 September 1890 |access-date=7 March 2020 |via=British Newspaper Archive |url-access=subscription  }}</ref> (afterwards station master at Aylesbury)\n*F. Butcher 1890 - 1893<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Railway Changes |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000415/18931007/076/0005 |newspaper=Herts Advertiser |location=England |date=7 October 1893 |access-date=7 March 2020 |via=British Newspaper Archive |url-access=subscription  }}</ref> (afterwards station master at Atherstone)\n*W.B. Holder 1893 - 1895<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=A new Station Master |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000415/18950518/092/0005 |newspaper=Herts Advertiser |location=England |date=18 May 1895 |access-date=7 March 2020 |via=British Newspaper Archive |url-access=subscription  }}</ref> (afterwards station master at Newport Pagnall)\n*Mr. Smerdon 1895 - 1896 (formerly station master at Stanmore)\n*William Telfer 1896 - 1905<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Departure of Mr. W. Telfer |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000415/19050916/096/0005 |newspaper=Herts Advertiser |location=England |date=16 September 1905 |access-date=7 March 2020 |via=British Newspaper Archive |url-access=subscription  }}</ref> (afterwards station master at Buxton)\n*Henry Orchard 1905 - 1912<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Hertfordshire |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000536/19120823/102/0007 |newspaper=Luton Times and Advertiser |location=England |date=23 August 1912 |access-date=7 March 2020 |via=British Newspaper Archive |url-access=subscription  }}</ref> (afterwards station master at Harrow Junction)\n{{Div col end}}\n{{Expand list|date=March 2020}}\n\n==Accidents and incidents==\n*On 10 February 1988, a [[diesel multiple unit]] overran the [[buffer stop]]. There were no injuries amongst the seventeen passengers on board.<ref name=NSES88>{{cite web |url=https://www.nsers.org/jan-dec-88.html |title=January 1988 to December 1988 |publisher=Network South East Railway Society |first=John P |last=McCrickard |date=6 October 2016 |accessdate=26 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Services==\nTrains operate to [[Watford Junction]] every 45 minutes Monday to Saturday daytime, every 60 minutes weekday evenings and on Sundays.\n\n{{rail start}}\n{{rail line|next=|previous=[[Park Street railway station (England)|Park Street]]|route=[[London Northwestern Railway]]<br/><small>[[Abbey Line]]</small> |col={{LNW colour}} }}\n{{Disused Rail Insert}} \n{{rail line|previous=|next = [[St Albans (London Road) railway station|St Albans<br/>(London Road)]]<br/><small>''Line and station closed''</small>|route=[[Great Northern Railway (Great Britain)|Great Northern Railway]]<br/><small>[[Hatfield and St Albans Railway]]|col={{GNR colour}} }}\n{{end box}}\n\n== References ==\n=== Notes ===\n<references />\n\n=== Sources ===\n* {{Butt-Stations}}\n* {{Jowett-Atlas}}\n* [http://www.abbeyline.org.uk/ Abbeyline.org.uk]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070928195717/http://www.stacc.org.uk/albanway/ The Alban Way]\n\n==External links==\n\n{{stn art lnk|SAA|OL146RR}}\n\n{{Hertfordshire railway stations}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saint Albans Abbey Railway Station}}\n[[Category:Transport in St Albans]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in Hertfordshire]]\n[[Category:Former London and North Western Railway stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1858]]\n[[Category:Railway stations served by West Midlands Trains]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox UK station\n| name         = St Albans Abbey\n| symbol       = rail\n| image_name   = St Albans Abbey railway station in 2009.jpg\n| code         = SAA\n| dft_category = F1\n| manager      = [[West Midlands Trains|London Northwestern Railway]]\n| locale       = [[St Albans]]\n